Chapter 1. Admin Guide

1.1. Overview

   The rust_credit_check module provides prepaid credit/balance
   checking with a per-worker HTTP cache. It queries an external
   billing API for account balances, caches results with a
   configurable TTL, and computes maximum call duration based on
   the balance and a per-minute rate.

   This module is useful for prepaid VoIP services where call
   authorization depends on available credit.

1.2. How it works

   When rust_credit_check() is called, the module first checks
   the per-worker cache for a valid (non-expired) balance entry
   for the account. On a cache hit, the cached balance is used
   immediately without any HTTP request.

   On a cache miss or expiry, the module sends a synchronous HTTP
   GET request to the billing API:

     GET {billing_url}?account={account}

   The API must return a JSON response with a "balance" field:

     {"balance": 42.50}

   Example 1.11. Billing API response format
   {"balance": 42.50}
   {"balance": 0}
   {"balance": -5.00}

   The balance is cached and then evaluated:
     * balance > 0: call is allowed. Max call duration is computed
       as (balance / rate_per_min) * 60 seconds.
     * balance <= 0: call is denied.

   On HTTP errors or unparseable responses, the on_error parameter
   controls whether the call is allowed or denied (fail-open vs
   fail-closed).

   The pseudo-variables $var(credit_balance) (string, 2 decimal
   places) and $var(credit_max_duration) (integer, seconds) are
   set on every call to rust_credit_check().

1.3. Dependencies

1.3.1. OpenSIPS Modules

   The following modules must be loaded before this module:
     * None.

1.3.2. External Libraries or Applications

   The following libraries or applications must be installed
   before running OpenSIPS with this module loaded:
     * None. HTTP client functionality is compiled into the Rust
       shared library.
     * An external billing API must be reachable at the configured
       billing_url.

1.4. Exported Parameters

1.4.1. billing_url (string)

   The base URL of the billing/balance API. The module appends
   "?account={account}" to form the full request URL. This
   parameter is required.

   Default value is "None" (must be set).

   Example 1.1. Set billing_url parameter
...
modparam("rust_credit_check", "billing_url", "http://billing:8080/balance")
...

1.4.2. cache_ttl (integer)

   Time-to-live in seconds for cached balance entries. After this
   period, the next rust_credit_check() call for the account will
   trigger a fresh HTTP query. Set to 0 to disable caching
   (not recommended for production).

   Default value is "300" (5 minutes).

   Example 1.2. Set cache_ttl parameter
...
modparam("rust_credit_check", "cache_ttl", 60)
...

1.4.3. http_timeout (integer)

   HTTP request timeout in seconds for billing API queries. If the
   API does not respond within this time, the on_error policy is
   applied.

   Default value is "2".

   Example 1.3. Set http_timeout parameter
...
modparam("rust_credit_check", "http_timeout", 5)
...

1.4.4. pool_size (integer)

   Number of HTTP connections to maintain per worker process.
   Connections are reused (keep-alive) for better performance.

   Default value is "4".

   Example 1.4. Set pool_size parameter
...
modparam("rust_credit_check", "pool_size", 8)
...

1.4.5. rate_per_min (integer)

   Cost units consumed per minute of call time. Used to compute
   the maximum call duration: max_duration = (balance / rate) * 60
   seconds. The result is set in $var(credit_max_duration).

   Default value is "1".

   Example 1.5. Set rate_per_min parameter
...
modparam("rust_credit_check", "rate_per_min", 2)
...

1.4.6. on_error (string)

   Behavior when the billing API is unreachable, returns a
   non-200 status, or returns unparseable JSON:

     * "deny" - reject the call (return -1). Fail-closed.
     * "allow" - allow the call (return 1). Fail-open.

   Case-insensitive comparison.

   Default value is "deny".

   Example 1.6. Set on_error parameter
...
modparam("rust_credit_check", "on_error", "allow")
...

1.4.7. tls_ca_file (string)

   Path to a custom CA certificate file (PEM format) for TLS
   verification of the billing API endpoint. If not set, the
   system default CA bundle is used.

   Default value is "None" (system defaults).

   Example 1.7. Set tls_ca_file parameter
...
modparam("rust_credit_check", "tls_ca_file", "/etc/ssl/certs/billing-ca.pem")
...

1.5. Exported Functions

1.5.1. rust_credit_check(account)

   Query the billing API (or per-worker cache) for the given
   account balance. On return, sets $var(credit_balance) and
   $var(credit_max_duration).

   Parameters:
     * account (string) - The account identifier to check.
       Typically $fU (From-URI username). This parameter is
       mandatory.

   Return values:
     * 1 - account has positive credit (call allowed)
     * -1 - account has zero or negative credit (call denied),
       or an error occurred and on_error is "deny"

   This function can be used from REQUEST_ROUTE, FAILURE_ROUTE,
   and ONREPLY_ROUTE.

   Example 1.8. rust_credit_check usage
...
route {
    if (is_method("INVITE") && !has_totag()) {
        if (!rust_credit_check("$fU")) {
            sl_send_reply(402, "Insufficient Credit");
            exit;
        }
        xlog("L_INFO", "$fU: balance=$var(credit_balance) max=$var(credit_max_duration)s\n");
    }
}
...

1.5.2. rust_credit_clear(account)

   Clear the cached balance entry for the given account. The next
   call to rust_credit_check() for this account will trigger a
   fresh HTTP query to the billing API.

   This is useful after a call ends to force a balance refresh, or
   when the billing system signals a balance change.

   Parameters:
     * account (string) - The account identifier whose cache entry
       should be cleared. This parameter is mandatory.

   Return values:
     * 1 - cache entry cleared (or was not present)
     * -1 - error (missing parameter or uninitialized worker)

   This function can be used from REQUEST_ROUTE, FAILURE_ROUTE,
   and ONREPLY_ROUTE.

   Example 1.9. rust_credit_clear usage
...
route {
    if (is_method("BYE")) {
        # Force balance refresh after call ends
        rust_credit_clear("$fU");
    }
}
...

1.6. Exported Pseudo-Variables

   The following pseudo-variables are set by rust_credit_check():

1.6.1. $var(credit_balance)

   The account balance as a string with 2 decimal places (e.g.,
   "42.50" or "0.00"). Set by rust_credit_check().

1.6.2. $var(credit_max_duration)

   The maximum call duration in seconds, computed as
   (balance / rate_per_min) * 60. Set as an integer by
   rust_credit_check(). A value of 0 means no credit available.

   Example 1.10. Complete opensips.cfg example
...
loadmodule "rust_credit_check.so"

modparam("rust_credit_check", "billing_url", "http://billing.internal:8080/balance")
modparam("rust_credit_check", "cache_ttl", 300)
modparam("rust_credit_check", "http_timeout", 2)
modparam("rust_credit_check", "pool_size", 4)
modparam("rust_credit_check", "rate_per_min", 1)
modparam("rust_credit_check", "on_error", "deny")

route {
    if (is_method("INVITE") && !has_totag()) {
        if (!rust_credit_check("$fU")) {
            xlog("L_WARN", "DENIED: $fU has insufficient credit ($var(credit_balance))\n");
            sl_send_reply(402, "Insufficient Credit");
            exit;
        }
        xlog("L_INFO", "ALLOWED: $fU balance=$var(credit_balance) max_dur=$var(credit_max_duration)s\n");
    }

    if (is_method("BYE")) {
        # Clear cache so next call gets fresh balance
        rust_credit_clear("$fU");
    }
}
...
